To find the product of two rational expressions, we multiply across, and simplify. [[☃ explanation 1]] 

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=} \dfrac{3(5z-6)}{(6-5z)(6+5z)}\cdot\dfrac{(5z+6)(5z+6)}{9(z^2+4)}
= \dfrac{3(5z-6) \cdot (5z+6)(5z+6)}{(6-5z)(6+5z) \cdot 9(z^2+4)}  &\text{Multiply across.}\\\\\\&=\dfrac{\cancel{\red{3}}\cdot -1\cancel{\green{(6-5z)}} \cancel{\purple{(5z+6)}}(5z+6)}{ \cancel{\red{3}}{ \cdot 3}\cancel{\green{(6-5z)}}\cancel{\purple{(6+5z)}} (z^2+4)} &\text{Cancel out common factors.}\\\\\\\\
&=-\dfrac{5z+6}{3(z^2+4)}\end{align}$

To divide two rational expressions, we flip the divisor, multiply across, then simplify: [[☃ explanation 1]] 

$\phantom{=} \dfrac{3k^2n}{(n+6k)(n-2k)} \div \dfrac{9kn^2}{(n+6k)(n+3k)} 
$

$\begin{align}
&= \dfrac{3k^2n}{(n\!+\!6k)(n\!-\!2k)} \cdot \dfrac{(n\!+\!6k)(n\!+\!3k)}{9kn^2} &\text{Flip the divisor.}\\\\\\\\
&=  \dfrac{3k^2n(n+6k)(n+3k)}{9kn^2(n+6k)(n-2k)}   &\text{Multiply across.}\\\\\\\\
&=  \dfrac{3 \cdot \green{\cancel{k}} \cdot k \cdot \purple{\cancel{n}} \pink{\cancel{(n+6k)}}(n+3k)}{9 \cdot \green{\cancel{k}} \cdot \purple{\cancel{n}} \cdot n \pink{\cancel{(n+6k)}}(n-2k)}    &\text{Cancel out common factors.}\\\\\\\\
&=\dfrac{k(n+3k)}{3n(n-2k)}
\end{align}$
